MCMC Simulation for Partial Order Inference

Bayesian Inference with Reversible Jump MCMC

BayesianPO Package

2025-05-27

Introduction

This tutorial demonstrates the Metropolis-Hastings Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MH-MCMC) process applied to partial orders, implementing the methodology described in Nicholls et al. (2024) using the BayesianPO R package.

The tutorial covers two main implementations:

  1. Fixed Dimension MCMC: Standard MCMC with fixed number of latent dimensions
  2. Reversible Jump MCMC: Variable dimension sampling that automatically determines optimal K

Key Features

  • Flexible Noise Models: Support for queue-jump and Mallows noise
  • Covariate Integration: Incorporation of external covariates
  • Reversible Jump MCMC: Automatic dimension selection
  • Convergence Diagnostics: Comprehensive monitoring tools

Mathematical Background

Partial Order Model

For and _ defined above, if we take:

\[U_{j,:} \sim N(0, \Sigma_\rho), \text{ independent for each } j \in M\] \[\eta_{j,:} = G^{-1}(\Phi(U_{j,:})) + \alpha_j \mathbf{1}_K^T\] \[y \sim p(\cdot|h(\eta(U, \beta)))\]

then \(h(\eta_{:,k}) \sim PL(\alpha; M)\) for each \(k = 1, \ldots, K\).

Queue Jump Error Model

Before the \(i\)-th entry \((y_i)\) is chosen: - There are \(m - i + 1\) elements remaining \((y_{i:m})\) - With probability \(p\): \(y_i\) is chosen randomly (ignoring order constraints) - With probability \((1-p)\): \(y_i\) is the maximal element in a random linear extension

The probability of a sequence \(y_{1:m}\) given poset \(h\) and noise parameter \(p\) is:

\[p_s(y_{1:m}|h, p) = \prod_{i=1}^{m-1} q(y_{i:m}|h[y_{i:m}], p)\]

where:

\[q(y_{i:m}|h[y_{i:m}], p) = \frac{p}{m-j+1} + (1-p)q_{y_{i:m}}(y_i|h[y_{i:m}])\]

Reversible Jump MCMC for Dimension Selection

The reversible jump MCMC extends the standard algorithm by allowing the dimension \(K\) to vary. The key moves are:

  • Birth move: \(K \rightarrow K+1\) by adding a new latent dimension
  • Death move: \(K \rightarrow K-1\) by removing a latent dimension

The acceptance probability includes: - Prior ratio: \(\frac{p(K')}{p(K)}\) - Likelihood ratio: \(\frac{p(y|K')}{p(y|K)}\) - Proposal ratio: \(\frac{q(K|K')}{q(K'|K)}\) - Jacobian term for the transformation

Data Generation

Generate Synthetic Partial Order

# Model parameters
n <- 6  # Number of items
N <- 30  # Number of total orders to sample
K <- 3   # Number of latent dimensions
p <- 2   # Number of covariates

# Generate true parameters
rho_true <- 0.7
prob_noise_true <- 0.1
beta_true <- c(0.5, -0.3)

# Create design matrix (p x n, where p is number of covariates)
X <- matrix(rnorm(p * n), nrow = p, ncol = n)

# Generate synthetic data
synthetic_data <- generate_synthetic_data(
  n_items = n,
  n_observations = N,
  K = K,
  rho_true = rho_true,
  prob_noise_true = prob_noise_true,
  beta_true = beta_true,
  X = t(X),  # transpose to make it n x p for the function
  random_seed = 42
)

# Extract components
items <- synthetic_data$items
observed_orders <- synthetic_data$observed_orders
choice_sets <- synthetic_data$choice_sets
h_true <- synthetic_data$h_true

cat("Generated partial order with", sum(h_true), "direct relationships\n")
## Generated partial order with 7 direct relationships
cat("Number of linear extensions:", count_linear_extensions(h_true), "\n")
## Number of linear extensions: 90

Visualize the True Partial Order

# Create visualization of the true partial order with clean styling
plot_partial_order(h_true, items, title = "True Partial Order", 
                  vertex_size = 25, edge_arrow_size = 0.4,
                  vertex_color = "lightgray", 
                  vertex_frame_color = "darkgray",
                  edge_color = "darkblue")

Standard MCMC Implementation

Fixed Dimension MCMC

# MCMC parameters
num_iterations <- 10000  # Reduced for faster demonstration
burn_in <- 200

# Update probabilities (must sum to 1)
mcmc_pt <- c(0.2, 0.2, 0.4, 0.2)  # rho, noise, U, beta

# Prior parameters
rho_prior <- 0.16667
noise_beta_prior <- 9.0
sigma_beta <- 1.0

# Run fixed dimension MCMC
mcmc_results <- mcmc_partial_order(
  observed_orders = observed_orders,
  choice_sets = choice_sets,
  num_iterations = num_iterations,
  K = K,
  X = X,
  dr = 0.1,                    # Multiplicative step for rho
  drbeta = 0.1,               # Step size for beta
  sigma_mallow = 0.1,         # Mallows parameter step
  sigma_beta = sigma_beta,
  noise_option = "queue_jump",
  mcmc_pt = mcmc_pt,
  rho_prior = rho_prior,
  noise_beta_prior = noise_beta_prior,
  mallow_ua = 10.0,
  random_seed = 42
)
## Starting MCMC with 10000 iterations...

Reversible Jump MCMC Implementation

The reversible jump MCMC allows the number of latent dimensions K to vary during sampling, automatically determining the optimal model complexity.

# Reversible Jump MCMC parameters
mcmc_pt_rj <- c(0.15, 0.15, 0.3, 0.15, 0.25)  # rho, noise, U, beta, K

# Prior for K (Poisson with rate K_prior)
K_prior <- 3.0

# Run Reversible Jump MCMC
rj_results <- mcmc_partial_order_k(
  observed_orders = observed_orders,
  choice_sets = choice_sets,
  num_iterations = num_iterations,
  X = X,
  dr = 0.1,
  drbeta = 0.1,
  sigma_mallow = 0.1,
  sigma_beta = sigma_beta,
  noise_option = "queue_jump",
  mcmc_pt = mcmc_pt_rj,
  rho_prior = rho_prior,
  noise_beta_prior = noise_beta_prior,
  mallow_ua = 10.0,
  K_prior = K_prior,

Model Comparison and Validation

Posterior Predictive Checks

# Calculate burn-in index (convert to trace index)
burn_in_index <- burn_in / 100  # Since we store every 100 iterations
threshold <- 0.5

# Extract post-burn-in partial order traces
h_trace_fixed_post_burnin <- mcmc_results$h_trace[(burn_in_index + 1):length(mcmc_results$h_trace)]
h_trace_rj_post_burnin <- rj_results$h_trace[(burn_in_index + 1):length(rj_results$h_trace)]

# Compute posterior mean partial orders
cat("Computing posterior mean partial orders...\n")
## Computing posterior mean partial orders...
# Fixed K MCMC: Average across all post-burn-in iterations
if (length(h_trace_fixed_post_burnin) > 0) {
  # Convert list of matrices to 3D array for easier averaging
  h_array_fixed <- array(0, dim = c(nrow(h_trace_fixed_post_burnin[[1]]), 
                                   ncol(h_trace_fixed_post_burnin[[1]]), 
                                   length(h_trace_fixed_post_burnin)))
  
  for (i in seq_along(h_trace_fixed_post_burnin)) {
    h_array_fixed[,,i] <- h_trace_fixed_post_burnin[[i]]
  }
  
  # Compute mean and apply threshold
  mean_h_fixed <- apply(h_array_fixed, c(1,2), mean)
  final_h_fixed <- (mean_h_fixed >= threshold) * 1
  
  # Apply transitive reduction to get minimal representation
  final_h_fixed <- transitive_reduction(final_h_fixed)
  
  cat("Fixed K MCMC: Averaged", length(h_trace_fixed_post_burnin), "post-burn-in samples\n")
} else {
  final_h_fixed <- matrix(0, nrow = nrow(h_true), ncol = ncol(h_true))
  cat("Warning: No post-burn-in samples for Fixed K MCMC\n")
}
## Fixed K MCMC: Averaged 98 post-burn-in samples
# RJ-MCMC: Average across all post-burn-in iterations
if (length(h_trace_rj_post_burnin) > 0) {
  # Convert list of matrices to 3D array for easier averaging
  h_array_rj <- array(0, dim = c(nrow(h_trace_rj_post_burnin[[1]]), 
                                ncol(h_trace_rj_post_burnin[[1]]), 
                                length(h_trace_rj_post_burnin)))
  
  for (i in seq_along(h_trace_rj_post_burnin)) {
    h_array_rj[,,i] <- h_trace_rj_post_burnin[[i]]
  }
  
  # Compute mean and apply threshold
  mean_h_rj <- apply(h_array_rj, c(1,2), mean)
  final_h_rj <- (mean_h_rj >= threshold) * 1
  
  # Apply transitive reduction to get minimal representation
  final_h_rj <- transitive_reduction(final_h_rj)
  
  cat("RJ-MCMC: Averaged", length(h_trace_rj_post_burnin), "post-burn-in samples\n")
} else {
  final_h_rj <- matrix(0, nrow = nrow(h_true), ncol = ncol(h_true))
  cat("Warning: No post-burn-in samples for RJ-MCMC\n")
}
## RJ-MCMC: Averaged 98 post-burn-in samples
# Compare with true partial order
accuracy_fixed <- sum(final_h_fixed == h_true) / length(h_true)
accuracy_rj <- sum(final_h_rj == h_true) / length(h_true)

cat("\nPartial Order Accuracy (using posterior mean with threshold", threshold, "):\n")

Posterior Uncertainty Analysis

# Analyze posterior uncertainty in partial order relationships
if (length(h_trace_fixed_post_burnin) > 0) {
  # Compute posterior probabilities for each edge
  posterior_probs_fixed <- apply(h_array_fixed, c(1,2), mean)
  
  # Create heatmap of posterior probabilities
  par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
  
  # Fixed K posterior probabilities
  image(posterior_probs_fixed, main = "Fixed K: Posterior Edge Probabilities", 
        xlab = "Item", ylab = "Item", col = heat.colors(100))
  
  # Histogram of posterior probabilities (only if we have positive probabilities)
  positive_probs_fixed <- posterior_probs_fixed[posterior_probs_fixed > 0]
  if (length(positive_probs_fixed) > 0) {
    hist(positive_probs_fixed, 
         main = "Fixed K: Distribution of Edge Probabilities",
         xlab = "Posterior Probability", ylab = "Frequency", 
         breaks = 20, col = "lightcoral")
    abline(v = threshold, col = "red", lty = 2, lwd = 2)
  } else {
    plot(1, type = "n", main = "Fixed K: No Positive Edge Probabilities",
         xlab = "Posterior Probability", ylab = "Frequency")
    text(1, 1, "No edges with positive probability", cex = 1.2)
  }
  
  if (length(h_trace_rj_post_burnin) > 0) {
    # RJ-MCMC posterior probabilities
    posterior_probs_rj <- apply(h_array_rj, c(1,2), mean)
    
    image(posterior_probs_rj, main = "RJ-MCMC: Posterior Edge Probabilities", 
          xlab = "Item", ylab = "Item", col = heat.colors(100))
    
    # Histogram of posterior probabilities (only if we have positive probabilities)
    positive_probs_rj <- posterior_probs_rj[posterior_probs_rj > 0]
    if (length(positive_probs_rj) > 0) {
      hist(positive_probs_rj, 
           main = "RJ-MCMC: Distribution of Edge Probabilities",
           xlab = "Posterior Probability", ylab = "Frequency", 
           breaks = 20, col = "lightgreen")
      abline(v = threshold, col = "red", lty = 2, lwd = 2)
    } else {
      plot(1, type = "n", main = "RJ-MCMC: No Positive Edge Probabilities",
           xlab = "Posterior Probability", ylab = "Frequency")
      text(1, 1, "No edges with positive probability", cex = 1.2)
    }
  } else {
    # Placeholder plots if no RJ-MCMC data
    plot(1, type = "n", main = "RJ-MCMC: No Data Available",
         xlab = "Item", ylab = "Item")
    plot(1, type = "n", main = "RJ-MCMC: No Data Available",
         xlab = "Posterior Probability", ylab = "Frequency")
  }
  
  par(mfrow = c(1, 1))
  
  # Report edges with high uncertainty
  cat("\nEdges with posterior probability between 0.2 and 0.8 (high uncertainty):\n")
  uncertain_edges_fixed <- which(posterior_probs_fixed > 0.2 & posterior_probs_fixed < 0.8, arr.ind = TRUE)
  if (nrow(uncertain_edges_fixed) > 0) {
    for (i in 1:nrow(uncertain_edges_fixed)) {
      row <- uncertain_edges_fixed[i, 1]
      col <- uncertain_edges_fixed[i, 2]
      prob <- posterior_probs_fixed[row, col]
      cat(sprintf("Fixed K: %s -> %s: %.3f\n", items[row], items[col], prob))
    }
  } else {
    cat("Fixed K: No highly uncertain edges found\n")
  }
  
  if (length(h_trace_rj_post_burnin) > 0) {
    uncertain_edges_rj <- which(posterior_probs_rj > 0.2 & posterior_probs_rj < 0.8, arr.ind = TRUE)
    if (nrow(uncertain_edges_rj) > 0) {
      for (i in 1:nrow(uncertain_edges_rj)) {
        row <- uncertain_edges_rj[i, 1]
        col <- uncertain_edges_rj[i, 2]
        prob <- posterior_probs_rj[row, col]
        cat(sprintf("RJ-MCMC: %s -> %s: %.3f\n", items[row], items[col], prob))
      }
    } else {
      cat("RJ-MCMC: No highly uncertain edges found\n")
    }
  }
} else {
  cat("No post-burn-in samples available for uncertainty analysis\n")
}

Advanced Features

MCMC Implementation Details

The mcmc_partial_order_k function implements the following update steps:

  1. Rho Update: Multiplicative random walk with step size dr
  2. Noise Parameter Update:
    • Queue-jump: Beta proposal
    • Mallows: Log-normal random walk
  3. Latent Matrix Update: Single row updates with multivariate normal proposals
  4. Beta Update: Component-wise normal random walk
  5. Dimension Update: Birth/death moves for K
# Example of manual parameter tuning
tuned_mcmc_pt <- c(0.1, 0.1, 0.4, 0.2, 0.2)  # Reduce K update frequency

# Run with different tuning
tuned_results <- mcmc_partial_order_k(
  observed_orders = observed_orders,
  choice_sets = choice_sets,
  num_iterations = 5000,  # Shorter run for demonstration
  X = X,
  dr = 1.05,              # Smaller step for rho
  drbeta = 0.05,          # Smaller step for beta
  sigma_mallow = 0.05,    # Smaller step for Mallows
  sigma_beta = sigma_beta,
  noise_option = "queue_jump",

Conclusion

This tutorial demonstrates the complete workflow for Bayesian partial order inference using the BayesianPO R package:

Key Findings

  1. Model Performance: Both fixed and reversible jump MCMC successfully recover the true partial order structure
  2. Dimension Selection: RJ-MCMC automatically identifies the optimal number of latent dimensions
  3. Parameter Estimation: Posterior estimates closely match true parameter values
  4. Computational Efficiency: The implementation provides good mixing and convergence

Advantages of Reversible Jump MCMC

  • Automatic Model Selection: No need to pre-specify the number of dimensions
  • Uncertainty Quantification: Provides posterior distribution over model complexity
  • Robust Inference: Less sensitive to initial parameter choices
  • Principled Comparison: Enables formal model comparison via marginal likelihoods

Best Practices

  1. Tuning: Adjust step sizes to achieve 20-50% acceptance rates
  2. Burn-in: Use sufficient burn-in period (typically 10-20% of total iterations)
  3. Convergence: Monitor trace plots and acceptance rates
  4. Multiple Chains: Run multiple chains to assess convergence

Extensions and Applications

The methodology can be extended to:

  • Hierarchical Models: Multi-level partial order structures
  • Time-Varying Orders: Dynamic partial order evolution
  • Missing Data: Handling incomplete observations
  • Large-Scale Problems: Scalable algorithms for big data

References

  • Nicholls, G. K., et al.(2024). Bayesian inference for partial orders. arXiv preprint arXiv:2212.05524.
  • Green, P. J. (1995). Reversible jump Markov chain Monte Carlo computation and Bayesian model determination. Biometrika, 82(4), 711-732.
